Analysis of the Carpentrys Long-Term Feedback Survey

Author: Kari L. Jordan Published: April 2017

Data and Software Carpentry launched a long-term assessment survey in March 2017. The goal of this survey is to hear from our learners about what has transpired in their work and career since completing a Carpentry workshop. Read our about our long-term assessment strategy on our blog and see how the community was involved with the development of this survey.

A PDF of the survey questions, the data used in this analysis, and the .RMD file are located in the long-term feedback survey report folder on GitHub. Feel free to use the data and tell us about your findings.

As of April 20, 2017, 510 learners have responded to the survey. Not all respondents answered each of the 26 questions.

Respondent Demographics

Provided below is a breakdown of our respondents by the Country where they attended a Carpentry workshop. A large portion of Carpentry learners responding to the survey attended a workshop in the United States. Additionally, a large number of our learners are Graduate Students.

Behaviors Adopted Post-Workshop

We asked our learners to identify the behaviors they adopted as a result of completing a Carpentry workshop. We are happy to report that more than half of the respondents who answered this question (n=395) have improved their data management and project organization practices, used programming languages for automation, and used version control to manage code.

Behaviors Adopted
Improving data management and project organization. 198
Developing a data management and analysis plan. 74
Using databases, scripts and queries to manage large data sets. 119
Transforming step-by-step workflows into scripts or functions. 111
Using programming languages like R or Python, or the command line to automate repetitive tasks. 260
Reusing code. 169
Using version control to manage code. 185
Using version control to collaborate online (in public or private repositories). 119
Sharing code or data publicly on places like GitHub or FigShare. 122

Learner Perception of Workshop Atmosphere

Using the Likert package, the following chart is an analysis of learner responses to the statements above.

cols_with_Agree <- map_lgl(data, ~`%in%`("Agree", .x))
data_agree <-  data[ , cols_with_Agree]

order = c("Strongly Disagree", "Disagree", "Neither Agree nor Disagree", "Agree", "Strongly Agree")

# How do I get the [1] data.frame not to show on the output? 
print(class(data_agree))
## [1] "data.frame"
data_agree <- map_if(data_agree,
                     is.character,
                     as.factor)

# Thanks Elizabeth for the tip!
for(i in seq_along(data_agree)) {
                data_agree[[i]] <- factor(data_agree[[i]], levels=order)
}

print(levels(data_agree))
## NULL
title <- "Workshops are Welcoming & Useful"
data_agree_likert <-  likert(as.data.frame(data_agree)) 
theme_update(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

plot(data_agree_likert) + ggtitle(title)
